    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for that, it helps to see the math. but it's still weird how much of the payment is just gone to interest at the start. it almost feels like there's some hidden factor or something working against me in the background, making the balance stay high even though I'm being consistent with my payments. does that happen because of the way compounding works or is there something else that can make it feel like the money is just being swallowed up?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You're right; how interest compounds plays a significant role in this, especially on a loan with a fixed interest rate and monthly payments. When you first borrow money, the interest is calculated on the entire principal amount. So more of your payments initially go toward interest rather than reducing the principal because the interest rate is applied to a higher balance. As a result, the principal balance doesn't decrease much, which can feel disheartening.\n\nCompounding occurs because each month's interest is calculated on the new balance, which is the previous month's balance minus your payment minus the interest for that month. If interest is compounded monthly, as it generally is for loans where interest is added monthly, the compound interest will gradually increase the total interest paid over the life of the loan. This compound interest not only adds up but also accelerates over time, which might explain how much of your payment seems to vanish in the early stages. Once you start reducing the principal more significantly as you pay off the loan, you'll find that more of your payments decrease the principal instead of just covering the interest. That's when you'll start seeing the impact of your payments on the total loan balance much more clearly.",
